WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.080 --> 00:00:01.640
Okay. Good afternoon, everybody.

2
00:00:02.440 --> 00:00:04.470
Thank you so much for joining us in this

3
00:00:05.280 --> 00:00:08.910
educational session called "When Tumors Act Like Viruses: Mechanisms and

4
00:00:08.960 --> 00:00:10.080
Therapeutic Frontiers."

5
00:00:10.920 --> 00:00:14.760
So in this session, we are going to provide a general overview

6
00:00:14.860 --> 00:00:16.540
of molecular mechanisms

7
00:00:17.620 --> 00:00:21.480
that explain the viral mimicry response in cancer, with a focus on the

8
00:00:21.490 --> 00:00:25.350
epigenetic mechanisms regulating this process and,

9
00:00:25.440 --> 00:00:29.220
in addition, the impact on the tumor microenvironment.

10
00:00:29.300 --> 00:00:29.820
We will

11
00:00:31.200 --> 00:00:35.180
explore a few targets that are able to induce this

12
00:00:35.220 --> 00:00:38.800
viral mimicry response in cancer and the effects on

13
00:00:38.870 --> 00:00:42.720
antitumor immunity and a potential role in enhancing

14
00:00:43.580 --> 00:00:44.520
responses to

15
00:00:45.380 --> 00:00:46.180
immunotherapy.

16
00:00:47.260 --> 00:00:50.720
So our speakers today will be

17
00:00:51.660 --> 00:00:53.160
Dr. Catherine Chapinelli,

18
00:00:54.560 --> 00:00:58.380
associate professor at the George Washington University in Washington,

19
00:00:58.440 --> 00:00:58.720
D.C.,

20
00:00:59.540 --> 00:00:59.870
and Dr.

21
00:01:01.040 --> 00:01:04.550
Nicolas Babret, an assistant professor at Icahn School of

22
00:01:04.621 --> 00:01:05.960
Medicine at Mount Sinai,

23
00:01:06.940 --> 00:01:10.750
and myself. My name is Israel Cañadas, and I'm an assistant professor

24
00:01:10.780 --> 00:01:12.020
at Fox Chase Cancer Center.

25
00:01:14.820 --> 00:01:16.540
So I will be the first speaker.

26
00:01:23.820 --> 00:01:24.160
Okay.

27
00:01:25.070 --> 00:01:26.600
And I'm going to talk today about

28
00:01:27.480 --> 00:01:31.340
how to turn a cold tumor hot and using viral mimicry as a

29
00:01:31.360 --> 00:01:33.760
therapeutic strategy in cancer.

30
00:01:34.960 --> 00:01:38.940
So I would like to start with a brief introduction of the concept

31
00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:42.170
of cold and hot tumors. As many of you will already know,

32
00:01:42.960 --> 00:01:46.560
cold tumors are these tumors that show a low immune infiltration,

33
00:01:47.700 --> 00:01:51.620
in other words, no presence of immune cells or very low presence of immune cells.

34
00:01:52.080 --> 00:01:55.940
And on the other hand, we have the hot tumors that are these tumors with

35
00:01:56.640 --> 00:02:00.240
high immune infiltration, presence of immune cells inside the tumors.

36
00:02:00.760 --> 00:02:02.300
Generally speaking,

37
00:02:03.140 --> 00:02:06.900
hot tumors or tumors with high presence of immune cells, in general, they

38
00:02:06.960 --> 00:02:10.160
show a better response to T cell checkpoint inhibition or other

39
00:02:10.259 --> 00:02:11.039
immunotherapy

40
00:02:12.160 --> 00:02:14.980
strategies. That's why there's a very

41
00:02:15.820 --> 00:02:19.620
high interest in the field about how we can turn this cold tumor

42
00:02:19.700 --> 00:02:20.040
hot.

43
00:02:20.840 --> 00:02:21.500
And one

44
00:02:22.620 --> 00:02:26.600
way to do that is enhancing innate immunity in

45
00:02:26.860 --> 00:02:30.540
cancer, right? So because if we are able to induce an innate immune response in

46
00:02:30.600 --> 00:02:34.460
the tumor microenvironment, this can be a way to

47
00:02:34.520 --> 00:02:38.240
turn this cold tumor hot. And already there are

48
00:02:38.620 --> 00:02:42.400
multiple current clinical trials of drugs that are

49
00:02:42.440 --> 00:02:46.100
targeting the innate immunity, highlighting the importance and the

50
00:02:46.140 --> 00:02:47.680
interest on these approaches.

51
00:02:48.860 --> 00:02:51.100
So already in the 20th century,

52
00:02:52.540 --> 00:02:56.380
there were some already indications trying

53
00:02:56.400 --> 00:03:00.130
this, specifically if we see what is called Coley's

54
00:03:00.180 --> 00:03:03.720
toxins. This was Dr. Coley's, that he already tried

55
00:03:04.660 --> 00:03:07.760
something like that. He injected bacteria

56
00:03:07.920 --> 00:03:10.489
into patients with cancer,

57
00:03:11.520 --> 00:03:14.660
basically with the purpose of inducing an immune response in the tumor

58
00:03:14.700 --> 00:03:17.660
microenvironment. And actually, the response was

59
00:03:18.440 --> 00:03:22.380
quite dramatic in some patients. However, and obviously also at the

60
00:03:22.420 --> 00:03:26.300
same time, were really big problems with infections,

61
00:03:27.160 --> 00:03:30.920
as you can imagine. But this was like a proof

62
00:03:30.960 --> 00:03:34.740
of concept that an immune response in the tumor can

63
00:03:34.800 --> 00:03:37.060
actually have an antitumor

64
00:03:38.020 --> 00:03:38.580
response.

65
00:03:40.680 --> 00:03:43.780
But then at this time was not yet

66
00:03:44.960 --> 00:03:48.060
discovered this concept of the viral mimicry response, and I would like to

67
00:03:48.100 --> 00:03:51.690
introduce these two studies that were the first time when

68
00:03:52.200 --> 00:03:56.140
really in the cancer field, we talk about this viral mimicry.

69
00:03:56.560 --> 00:03:56.820
So

70
00:03:57.800 --> 00:04:01.360
these were two studies where

71
00:04:01.620 --> 00:04:05.350
inhibition of DNA methylation was inducing an immune response,

72
00:04:05.520 --> 00:04:09.280
and the mechanism was through the reactivation

73
00:04:09.400 --> 00:04:13.160
of endogenous retroviruses, that at the same time, they were

74
00:04:13.600 --> 00:04:17.300
generating double-strand RNA, these cytosolic nucleases

75
00:04:17.700 --> 00:04:20.800
that were triggering an innate immune response

76
00:04:21.240 --> 00:04:25.080
and enhancing responses to immunotherapy.

77
00:04:26.620 --> 00:04:30.600
So what is viral mimicry? It's the activation of innate

78
00:04:30.640 --> 00:04:32.630
immune signaling pathways in cancer

79
00:04:33.660 --> 00:04:37.300
cells driven by the aberrant accumulation of cytoplasmic

80
00:04:37.400 --> 00:04:41.170
nucleases. So where these cytosolic

81
00:04:41.220 --> 00:04:44.160
nucleases are coming from? Because they are endogenous

82
00:04:44.860 --> 00:04:48.200
cytosolic nucleases. Basically, from the reactivation of silenced

83
00:04:48.400 --> 00:04:52.160
transposable elements, including lines, signs, and

84
00:04:52.200 --> 00:04:53.440
endogenous retroviruses.

85
00:04:54.660 --> 00:04:58.300
These transposable elements, they are recognized by

86
00:04:58.320 --> 00:05:00.480
cytosolic pattern recognition receptors

87
00:05:02.340 --> 00:05:05.960
that can include RIG-I-like receptors, like

88
00:05:06.020 --> 00:05:09.680
MDA5 or RIG-I, or toll-like receptors, like

89
00:05:09.700 --> 00:05:13.240
TLR3 or others, that they can recognize double-strand

90
00:05:13.360 --> 00:05:17.100
RNA, but also the cGAS-STING pathway that can recognize

91
00:05:17.140 --> 00:05:18.240
double-strand DNA.

92
00:05:19.220 --> 00:05:22.520
So downstream effects of this response

93
00:05:22.620 --> 00:05:26.180
basically involve an interferon response and the induction of

94
00:05:26.200 --> 00:05:29.880
MHC class I, which can clearly make these tumor cells more

95
00:05:29.900 --> 00:05:33.780
immunogenic. And as you can imagine, this has a big

96
00:05:33.800 --> 00:05:34.960
therapeutic relevance.

97
00:05:36.180 --> 00:05:39.570
Multiple epigenetic therapies, including DNMT, EHZ2,

98
00:05:39.740 --> 00:05:40.880
LSD1, et cetera,

99
00:05:42.480 --> 00:05:43.610
CDK inhibitors,

100
00:05:44.600 --> 00:05:48.560
all these different therapeutic relevant, clinically relevant drugs are able

101
00:05:48.600 --> 00:05:52.530
to induce this viral mimicry, and there's a clear impact on the

102
00:05:52.580 --> 00:05:54.450
tumor microenvironment and the immunotherapy

103
00:05:54.620 --> 00:05:58.220
response.So there are different

104
00:05:58.240 --> 00:06:02.040
histone targets that can induce the viral mimicry, including

105
00:06:02.100 --> 00:06:06.020
histone methyltransferases, the methylases, or the

106
00:06:06.040 --> 00:06:09.600
acetylases. But also there are other non-histone targets,

107
00:06:09.800 --> 00:06:13.260
including cyclin-dependent kinases, spliceosome target therapies,

108
00:06:13.360 --> 00:06:17.000
DNA/RNA helicases, and also dsRNA or dsDNA

109
00:06:17.060 --> 00:06:20.240
negative regulators like ADAR or TREX1.

110
00:06:22.280 --> 00:06:25.820
So I would like also to briefly introduce this

111
00:06:26.120 --> 00:06:29.299
paradox that I find that is quite interesting

112
00:06:30.000 --> 00:06:33.440
because a chronic viral mimicry can also induce immune evasion.

113
00:06:34.100 --> 00:06:37.620
So far I was explaining how this viral mimicry can have a big impact

114
00:06:37.660 --> 00:06:40.700
in inducing innate immunity, right?

115
00:06:41.240 --> 00:06:45.080
But recently this study show how actually

116
00:06:45.100 --> 00:06:47.240
chronic viral mimicry can also induce

117
00:06:48.480 --> 00:06:51.440
immune evasion. So how this is happening,

118
00:06:52.240 --> 00:06:55.460
for example, the example reported in that

119
00:06:55.960 --> 00:06:59.260
study was through the p53 loss, very common in a lot of

120
00:06:59.300 --> 00:07:03.270
cancers. So this p53 loss is inducing a transcription

121
00:07:03.300 --> 00:07:07.040
of immunogenic repetitive elements that this is going to

122
00:07:07.060 --> 00:07:10.700
induce a viral mimicry response that actually can

123
00:07:10.740 --> 00:07:14.280
control the growth of early cancer

124
00:07:14.380 --> 00:07:18.220
cells. So after this viral mimicry becomes chronic

125
00:07:18.380 --> 00:07:22.240
through the constant activation of this immune response through immunogenic

126
00:07:22.300 --> 00:07:24.140
repetitive elements, some

127
00:07:24.960 --> 00:07:28.360
cancer cells can actually tolerate these cytosolic

128
00:07:28.420 --> 00:07:32.180
nucleases and some of these clones actually can reduce

129
00:07:32.200 --> 00:07:35.920
immunogenicity, and in that way they can promote immune

130
00:07:35.980 --> 00:07:39.820
evasion. At the same time, this understanding the mechanisms

131
00:07:39.880 --> 00:07:40.340
that can

132
00:07:41.540 --> 00:07:41.960
induce this

133
00:07:43.520 --> 00:07:46.840
tolerance to cytosolic nucleases can open new windows of therapeutic

134
00:07:46.880 --> 00:07:47.540
opportunity.

135
00:07:49.160 --> 00:07:49.320
So,

136
00:07:51.060 --> 00:07:54.940
the viral mimicry can also be induced in lung

137
00:07:55.020 --> 00:07:58.380
cancer, and this is some of our previous work in which

138
00:07:58.440 --> 00:08:02.300
in specific populations of small cell lung cancer

139
00:08:02.920 --> 00:08:06.900
cells, we were able to see that they spontaneously were more

140
00:08:06.980 --> 00:08:10.100
immunogenic than isogenic parental cells.

141
00:08:10.620 --> 00:08:14.300
So we found actually that these cells were in an

142
00:08:14.320 --> 00:08:18.000
epigenetic state allowing the reactivation of some of these endogenous

143
00:08:18.020 --> 00:08:21.900
retroviruses, that we call them SPARCs, and generating

144
00:08:21.920 --> 00:08:25.280
this double-strand RNA that can trigger an innate immune response.

145
00:08:25.860 --> 00:08:29.660
So we observed that actually these ERVs

146
00:08:29.700 --> 00:08:33.160
were correlated with antigen presentation, EMT,

147
00:08:33.620 --> 00:08:37.321
immune evasion, but also associated to some epigenetics

148
00:08:38.081 --> 00:08:41.780
factors or chromatin modifiers related with this epigenetic

149
00:08:42.000 --> 00:08:42.380
state.

150
00:08:44.201 --> 00:08:44.380
So,

151
00:08:45.760 --> 00:08:49.720
then we are using this concept trying to

152
00:08:49.840 --> 00:08:52.200
turn cold small cell lung cancers tumor hot.

153
00:08:52.280 --> 00:08:54.940
Small cell lung cancer is a clear example of a cold tumor,

154
00:08:55.780 --> 00:08:59.430
very low immune infiltration and really aggressive and

155
00:08:59.460 --> 00:09:03.400
difficult to treat tumor. So then we think that inducing an immune

156
00:09:03.440 --> 00:09:07.380
response in the tumor microenvironment of these tumors can

157
00:09:07.400 --> 00:09:11.160
be an effective way to make them more sensitive to different kind of

158
00:09:11.180 --> 00:09:14.960
therapies. So far we have identified a

159
00:09:15.000 --> 00:09:18.800
few targets that are able to induce that in this context,

160
00:09:19.160 --> 00:09:22.200
including RNA helicase DSH9,

161
00:09:22.280 --> 00:09:25.500
deoxynuclease TREX1, or the spliceosome.

162
00:09:26.380 --> 00:09:30.100
Inhibiting these different factors that they are

163
00:09:30.360 --> 00:09:31.180
viral mimicry

164
00:09:32.120 --> 00:09:35.850
inducers, we can actually induce the accumulation of different

165
00:09:36.260 --> 00:09:40.160
nucleases, including dsRNA, dsDNA, R-loops,

166
00:09:40.500 --> 00:09:44.020
but also less common forms of dsRNA like zeRNA.

167
00:09:44.540 --> 00:09:48.200
And this, at the end of the day, will induce this interferon response,

168
00:09:48.280 --> 00:09:52.060
DNA damage, cytokines, tissue presentation, and the viral

169
00:09:52.120 --> 00:09:55.580
immune response, which will make these tumors more

170
00:09:55.640 --> 00:09:56.340
immunogenic.

171
00:09:57.540 --> 00:09:57.740
So,

172
00:09:58.900 --> 00:10:02.500
we were very interested in identifying targets to induce

173
00:10:02.540 --> 00:10:06.340
this dsRNA accumulation in cancer cells.

174
00:10:06.700 --> 00:10:10.650
So using small cell lung cancer as a model, we perform a CRISPR screen of

175
00:10:10.660 --> 00:10:14.139
RNA helicases and measure dsRNA

176
00:10:14.200 --> 00:10:17.740
accumulation. And in that way, it was how we

177
00:10:17.780 --> 00:10:21.740
identify DSH9 being one of the targets inducing

178
00:10:21.750 --> 00:10:23.740
higher accumulation of double-strand RNA.

179
00:10:24.240 --> 00:10:27.900
And actually, interestingly, DSH9 expression

180
00:10:28.000 --> 00:10:28.320
was

181
00:10:29.540 --> 00:10:32.160
quite high, specifically in small cell lung cancer.

182
00:10:32.980 --> 00:10:36.860
So as I mentioned, we were able to see after DSH9 depletion,

183
00:10:37.020 --> 00:10:40.180
this accumulation of double-strand RNA,

184
00:10:40.720 --> 00:10:44.460
dsRNA. And after sequencing this dsRNA and performing

185
00:10:44.500 --> 00:10:48.240
RIP-seq, actually, we found that it was enriched in different

186
00:10:48.250 --> 00:10:51.880
retroelements, including SINEs, LINEs or LTRs.

187
00:10:53.920 --> 00:10:57.720
Interestingly, we also observed that the deletion of DSH9

188
00:10:58.100 --> 00:11:01.930
can also induce the accumulation of DNA-RNA hybrids in

189
00:11:01.960 --> 00:11:02.740
the cells.

190
00:11:03.660 --> 00:11:07.520
After RNA sequencing of these cells, we were able to see that actually a

191
00:11:07.580 --> 00:11:11.520
clear immune response, but also DNA damage was

192
00:11:11.600 --> 00:11:15.500
triggered after DSH9 knockout, and this was related with the accumulation

193
00:11:15.560 --> 00:11:19.520
of the dsRNA, but also DNA damage derived from this

194
00:11:19.660 --> 00:11:22.300
DNA-RNA hybrids induction.

195
00:11:23.360 --> 00:11:26.900
We found that this response, this interferon

196
00:11:26.980 --> 00:11:29.180
signaling, was dependent on

197
00:11:30.520 --> 00:11:33.100
both STING and MABS. After knocking out

198
00:11:34.080 --> 00:11:37.880
STING and MABS, we were able to rescue the induction, for example, here of

199
00:11:37.940 --> 00:11:40.460
interferon beta induced by DSH9 knockdown,

200
00:11:41.560 --> 00:11:45.420
and also some clear markers of innate immunity like for TBK1 or

201
00:11:45.460 --> 00:11:49.380
for IR3. After both sensors were

202
00:11:49.400 --> 00:11:53.280
deleted, we were not able to see this phosphorylation

203
00:11:53.320 --> 00:11:56.580
of TBK1 or IR3, very common after an innate immune

204
00:11:56.620 --> 00:11:59.648
activation.We wanted to translate that

205
00:12:00.128 --> 00:12:04.008
to in vivo, and then we took

206
00:12:04.028 --> 00:12:06.508
advantage of our small cell lung cancer mouse model.

207
00:12:07.508 --> 00:12:11.328
We inoculated, in an immunocompetent model, mouse's small cell lung

208
00:12:11.368 --> 00:12:13.268
cancer cells, and we

209
00:12:14.408 --> 00:12:17.848
induced the knockdown of DSH9. And this

210
00:12:18.008 --> 00:12:21.968
significantly decreased the tumor growth, and also was

211
00:12:21.988 --> 00:12:24.988
correlated with an increase in CD8 T cells.

212
00:12:25.448 --> 00:12:29.328
This motivated us to repeat same experiment, but in that case, also treating

213
00:12:29.388 --> 00:12:29.548
with

214
00:12:30.628 --> 00:12:34.528
anti-PD-1. And actually, the combination of anti-PD-1 with

215
00:12:34.788 --> 00:12:38.508
the deletion of DSH9 dramatically improved the

216
00:12:38.628 --> 00:12:42.148
response to immunotherapy, but also their survival.

217
00:12:44.468 --> 00:12:44.648
So

218
00:12:45.508 --> 00:12:49.208
the dsRNA has been clearly showed to induce this viral mimicry

219
00:12:49.218 --> 00:12:52.888
response. But we were also interested in less common forms of

220
00:12:52.928 --> 00:12:53.488
dsRNA,

221
00:12:54.488 --> 00:12:57.488
like for example, crRNA, that this is a left-handed

222
00:12:58.128 --> 00:13:01.908
orientation of the regular dsRNA that is called a RNA, that has

223
00:13:01.968 --> 00:13:02.148
been,

224
00:13:03.268 --> 00:13:07.048
in the last year, show that actually can induce viral mimicry

225
00:13:07.388 --> 00:13:09.648
through CBP1-dependent necroptosis

226
00:13:11.028 --> 00:13:15.008
after viral infection, but also in some

227
00:13:15.088 --> 00:13:18.268
cancer models. So inspired by

228
00:13:19.628 --> 00:13:23.228
this work and others where spliceosome inhibitors were

229
00:13:23.248 --> 00:13:27.008
inducing viral mimicry through the accumulation of double-stranded RNA, we

230
00:13:27.068 --> 00:13:30.828
check if actually spliceosome inhibitors were able to also

231
00:13:31.148 --> 00:13:34.628
induce an accumulation of crRNA, and it was like that.

232
00:13:34.748 --> 00:13:38.528
In different mouse and human small cell lung cancer cell lines, we clearly

233
00:13:38.548 --> 00:13:41.028
observed this increase in crRNAs.

234
00:13:42.208 --> 00:13:42.788
And after

235
00:13:43.868 --> 00:13:47.808
pull down the crRNAs and sequencing them, or in other words, after doing

236
00:13:47.848 --> 00:13:50.888
RIP-seq, we were able to see actually, after

237
00:13:51.448 --> 00:13:55.268
SF3B1 inhibition with this pladinolide B, or PlB,

238
00:13:56.028 --> 00:13:59.628
a clear shift, an accumulation of an

239
00:13:59.768 --> 00:14:03.508
induction of intron retention. So when we

240
00:14:04.048 --> 00:14:07.448
check these genes with intron retentions, actually they were clearly

241
00:14:07.508 --> 00:14:11.288
enriched in cells treated with this SF3B1

242
00:14:11.388 --> 00:14:14.828
inhibitor. And we also observed that some of the

243
00:14:14.968 --> 00:14:17.788
genes were enriched with the presence of,

244
00:14:18.648 --> 00:14:22.528
in that case, science elements with the potential capacity of generating

245
00:14:22.548 --> 00:14:26.268
these secondary structures that can trigger an immune response.

246
00:14:27.168 --> 00:14:27.368
So

247
00:14:28.668 --> 00:14:32.528
this crRNA can be sensed by CBP1, and it will trigger this

248
00:14:32.548 --> 00:14:36.028
RIPK3/MLKL-dependent necroptosis, that is an

249
00:14:36.128 --> 00:14:39.988
immunogenic cell death. And we actually

250
00:14:40.048 --> 00:14:43.528
observed that this necroptosis was dependent on

251
00:14:43.588 --> 00:14:46.668
CBP1 after cells were treated with this

252
00:14:47.208 --> 00:14:51.068
spliceosome inhibitor. This FOSL/MLKL activation

253
00:14:51.208 --> 00:14:55.108
also indicate necroptosis after the treatment with a spliceosome inhibitor

254
00:14:55.448 --> 00:14:59.428
was only observed in cells overexpressing CBP1, but not in cells

255
00:14:59.508 --> 00:15:03.368
with no expression of CBP1. And also

256
00:15:03.428 --> 00:15:07.228
the mutation of one important domain necessary for the

257
00:15:07.308 --> 00:15:11.188
detection of crRNAs, this C alpha domain, when we mutated that,

258
