00:32:11.864 --> 00:32:12.104
Yeah.

569
00:32:12.184 --> 00:32:15.604
So the combination of both is what we think that is

570
00:32:15.684 --> 00:32:16.484
inducing this

571
00:32:17.404 --> 00:32:21.084
immune response associated also to the DNA damage and cell death.

572
00:32:21.504 --> 00:32:25.264
And at the end of the day, that's why we are seeing this decrease in

573
00:32:25.303 --> 00:32:28.904
tumor growth, but also the potentiation of the PD-1, TP1

574
00:32:28.964 --> 00:32:29.364
therapy.

575
00:32:30.804 --> 00:32:30.984
Okay.

576
00:32:32.504 --> 00:32:36.294
Okay. Thank you so much for the interesting questions, and now is

577
00:32:36.384 --> 00:32:39.904
the turn of Dr. Katherine Chiappinelli. Thank you so much.

578
00:32:48.224 --> 00:32:52.144
Good afternoon, everyone. Thank you for the invitation to present our work at this

579
00:32:52.184 --> 00:32:53.164
educational session.

580
00:32:54.044 --> 00:32:58.024
I'm going to focus on specifically epigenetic regulation of viral mimicry responses

581
00:32:58.064 --> 00:32:58.584
in cancer.

582
00:33:02.364 --> 00:33:02.544
So

583
00:33:03.404 --> 00:33:07.394
when we think about treating cancer with epigenetic drugs, this was

584
00:33:07.444 --> 00:33:10.444
first done in the context of reactivating tumor suppressors.

585
00:33:10.744 --> 00:33:14.604
Just as tumor suppressor genes can be mutated to turn off their function, they

586
00:33:14.624 --> 00:33:18.084
can also have epigenetic alterations.

587
00:33:18.164 --> 00:33:22.024
One of which is DNA methylation, which is a covalent modification of the DNA

588
00:33:22.064 --> 00:33:25.964
itself, which will have methyl binding domain proteins bind to it to compact the

589
00:33:25.984 --> 00:33:29.924
chromatin. This can be reversed by DNMT inhibitors, including

590
00:33:29.964 --> 00:33:30.664
AZA and DAC.

591
00:33:31.584 --> 00:33:35.044
In addition, there are many modifications to the histone proteins themselves that

592
00:33:35.064 --> 00:33:38.764
can be activating or repressive. One drug that is used in cancers are called

593
00:33:38.924 --> 00:33:42.564
HDAC inhibitors, and these inhibit the enzymes that take off acetyl

594
00:33:42.624 --> 00:33:46.214
groups. If you think about it, an acetyl group has a negative charge, and when it's

595
00:33:46.244 --> 00:33:50.084
added to a positively charged histone, it pushes away the negatively charged

596
00:33:50.124 --> 00:33:53.884
DNA, opening up the chromatin. So the original goal of both of these

597
00:33:53.924 --> 00:33:57.744
kinds of cancer drugs was to turn on gene expression of silenced tumor

598
00:33:57.804 --> 00:33:58.304
suppressors.

599
00:33:59.904 --> 00:34:03.224
And as you've heard from the previous talk, another very important role of these

600
00:34:03.264 --> 00:34:06.904
epigenetic drugs is actually through stimulation of innate immune signaling.

601
00:34:07.164 --> 00:34:11.044
So we in the De Carvalho lab published back-to-back papers showing that DNMT

602
00:34:11.084 --> 00:34:14.524
inhibitors remove DNA methylation across the genome, resulting in

603
00:34:14.564 --> 00:34:16.984
transcription of transposable element RNAs.

604
00:34:17.644 --> 00:34:21.424
These are sensed by proteins that would normally sense viral double-stranded RNA.

605
00:34:21.544 --> 00:34:24.864
It's more of an RNA hairpin structure that activates these sensors,

606
00:34:26.265 --> 00:34:30.245
resulting in type I interferon signaling and intrinsic cancer cell death, as

607
00:34:30.284 --> 00:34:32.804
well as recruitment and activation of host immune cells.

608
00:34:34.223 --> 00:34:38.194
Beyond DNA methylation, we and others have shown that HDAC inhibitors

609
00:34:38.223 --> 00:34:42.124
can improve this response. HDAC inhibitors alone do not seem to be enough

610
00:34:42.185 --> 00:34:46.165
to reactivate teRNA, but when you add HDAC inhibitors, this response is

611
00:34:46.245 --> 00:34:46.725
increased.

612
00:34:48.225 --> 00:34:52.185
Others have shown very nicely that when you inhibit histone methyltransferases, the

613
00:34:52.205 --> 00:34:55.455
enzymes that add repressive marks to histones, you also see this induction of

614
00:34:55.484 --> 00:34:58.624
teRNA and resulting type I interferon response.

615
00:34:59.944 --> 00:35:03.764
Finally, cancers that harbor mutation in chromatin regulators

616
00:35:03.864 --> 00:35:07.804
also exhibit TE upregulation baseline and this viral mimicry signature.

617
00:35:08.804 --> 00:35:12.344
So I wanted to summarize about a decade of work here to show that when you

618
00:35:12.424 --> 00:35:16.014
disrupt chromatin compaction in cancer, one of the biggest phenotypes is

619
00:35:16.044 --> 00:35:19.804
transcription of RNA from transposable elements activating type I interferon

620
00:35:19.844 --> 00:35:20.264
signaling.

621
00:35:22.164 --> 00:35:24.664
And these transposable elements are about half of our genome.

622
00:35:24.824 --> 00:35:27.964
They were discovered by Barbara McClintock, who won the Nobel Prize for this work,

623
00:35:28.414 --> 00:35:31.904
and she discovered them in corn. So, when you think about a

624
00:35:31.964 --> 00:35:35.874
transposable element, the simplest definition of it is a piece of DNA that can

625
00:35:35.904 --> 00:35:37.924
move about the genome of its own accord.

626
00:35:38.444 --> 00:35:42.244
So on this corn cob here, you can see yellow kernels and red

627
00:35:42.284 --> 00:35:46.184
kernels, and then you can see a modeled kernel here, and that is the

628
00:35:46.204 --> 00:35:49.454
result of a transposable element hopping into a gene that would encode, for

629
00:35:49.504 --> 00:35:52.744
example, red or yellow pigment. And this is how she discovered this.

630
00:35:54.064 --> 00:35:57.834
And in the human genome on the right here, this pie chart, we have about

631
00:35:57.924 --> 00:36:01.384
half transposable elements. And I want to clarify that most of these cannot move

632
00:36:01.424 --> 00:36:04.084
about the genome anymore. They have not been conserved through evolution.

633
00:36:04.644 --> 00:36:07.264
However, they can make RNA and protein.

634
00:36:07.344 --> 00:36:10.804
So you have about 8% endogenous retroviral or LTR elements,

635
00:36:11.224 --> 00:36:13.664
remnants of old viruses that integrated into our genome.

636
00:36:14.064 --> 00:36:17.604
These can make RNA and proteins, likely not particles, and they can likely not

637
00:36:17.624 --> 00:36:18.524
retro transpose.

638
00:36:19.384 --> 00:36:21.444
About 20% of the genome are line elements.

639
00:36:21.784 --> 00:36:24.564
About 100 of these loci have the ability to retro

640
00:36:24.644 --> 00:36:28.432
transpose.And then SINE elements or Alu elements, these

641
00:36:28.532 --> 00:36:32.212
make RNAs in general, a lot of these immunogenic double-strand RNA species.

642
00:36:34.212 --> 00:36:37.592
In healthy differentiated cells, most of these transposable elements are

643
00:36:37.692 --> 00:36:41.362
silenced by chromatin modifications, including DNA methylation and

644
00:36:41.392 --> 00:36:45.152
histone modifications. And during the global epigenetic dysregulation that

645
00:36:45.192 --> 00:36:49.182
occurs when cells go from normal to cancer, a lot of them lose their

646
00:36:49.232 --> 00:36:52.892
epigenetic silencing and are generally expressed at higher levels in cancers than

647
00:36:52.932 --> 00:36:53.591
normal cells.

648
00:36:55.372 --> 00:36:59.012
And as a result of this viral mimicry induction by epigenetic therapies,

649
00:36:59.532 --> 00:37:01.532
we've shown that you can sensitize to immune therapy.

650
00:37:01.952 --> 00:37:05.332
This is in a melanoma model where we're looking at the tumor growing.

651
00:37:05.372 --> 00:37:08.872
This is untreated and then treated with anti CTLA-4 checkpoint blockade.

652
00:37:09.412 --> 00:37:13.372
This is DNMT inhibitor alone, four doses, and the combination therapy is

653
00:37:13.412 --> 00:37:14.432
better than either one alone.

654
00:37:15.612 --> 00:37:19.152
In an aggressive model, a murines model of ovarian cancer, we're measuring survival

655
00:37:19.162 --> 00:37:23.092
here. The black is untreated, and then the gray

656
00:37:23.132 --> 00:37:26.972
is PD-1 alone, and then the orange is the combination of epigenetic therapy and

657
00:37:27.012 --> 00:37:30.891
anti PD-1. And so just as was very nicely demonstrated in the previous talk, these

658
00:37:30.932 --> 00:37:34.612
epigenetic drugs can also sensitize to immune checkpoint blockade in murines models

659
00:37:34.632 --> 00:37:35.092
of cancer.

660
00:37:36.472 --> 00:37:39.772
These have been translated to clinical trials, which I've tried to summarize here,

661
00:37:39.852 --> 00:37:41.172
I think this is not all of them,

662
00:37:42.152 --> 00:37:44.372
targeting multiple different kinds of tumors.

663
00:37:44.432 --> 00:37:46.592
And really these results have been quite mixed,

664
00:37:47.572 --> 00:37:51.552
where in ovarian cancer, there's not been a lot of responses, in lung

665
00:37:51.592 --> 00:37:52.312
cancer as well.

666
00:37:53.332 --> 00:37:57.212
But when you look at this melanoma trial, this was promising.

667
00:37:57.252 --> 00:38:01.191
It's going to phase two. And I would say the most promising one recently was

668
00:38:01.212 --> 00:38:04.992
this trial in NKT cell lymphoma, where patients that were refractory to

669
00:38:05.032 --> 00:38:08.672
anti PD-1 were given DNMT inhibitors and then

670
00:38:08.712 --> 00:38:10.752
became sensitive to this immune checkpoint blockade.

671
00:38:11.372 --> 00:38:14.452
And so I think the spectrum of clinical trials shows that there's still a lot that

672
00:38:14.492 --> 00:38:18.312
we don't know about how this works actually in the patients, and especially in

673
00:38:18.372 --> 00:38:21.592
terms of resistance to this viral mimicry, which was discussed very nicely in the

674
00:38:21.632 --> 00:38:22.292
previous talk.

675
00:38:23.992 --> 00:38:27.592
So one thing that can drive resistance to viral mimicry is editing of these

676
00:38:27.612 --> 00:38:30.872
immunogenic RNAs. So when you have transcription of these RNAs,

677
00:38:31.792 --> 00:38:33.832
they are making these hairpin structures.

678
00:38:33.892 --> 00:38:37.592
And Pari Mehtapoor and Daniel de Carvalho showed that these are edited by the ADAR1

679
00:38:37.632 --> 00:38:40.592
enzyme. That's an A to I edit, which is read as a G.

680
00:38:41.032 --> 00:38:44.932
And when you think about an RNA hairpin, it's going to relax the hairpin so that

681
00:38:44.952 --> 00:38:48.231
it doesn't bind as well to MDA5 and activate immune signaling.

682
00:38:49.112 --> 00:38:53.092
So my PhD student, Stephanie Gomez, wanted to understand how this affected

683
00:38:53.332 --> 00:38:55.692
the tumor immune microenvironment.

684
00:38:55.752 --> 00:38:59.122
And this is an aggressive murines model of ovarian cancer,

685
00:38:59.692 --> 00:39:02.812
and if you look at the survival in the gray curve,

686
00:39:03.212 --> 00:39:04.992
untreated, they're all dead by week nine.

687
00:39:05.432 --> 00:39:08.072
You can increase survival with the DNMT inhibitor in red.

688
00:39:08.912 --> 00:39:12.712
ADAR1 knockdown further increases survival, and the combination of both is much

689
00:39:12.732 --> 00:39:16.192
better than either one alone. So in this case, inhibiting RNA editing plus DNA

690
00:39:16.212 --> 00:39:17.832
methylation was much better.

691
00:39:19.462 --> 00:39:22.692
And this was really due to reversal of the immune suppressive tumor

692
00:39:22.752 --> 00:39:26.012
microenvironment, where you can see there's fewer M2-like macrophages,

693
00:39:26.612 --> 00:39:30.492
fewer myeloid-derived suppressor cells, more M1-like macrophages,

694
00:39:30.932 --> 00:39:33.572
and more natural killer cells. This is really consistent with a type one

695
00:39:33.612 --> 00:39:35.981
interferon-driven change in the tumor microenvironment.

696
00:39:38.352 --> 00:39:39.921
And to determine what was causing this,

697
00:39:40.852 --> 00:39:44.442
Stephanie took our best surviving group, which is the solid purple line here, and

698
00:39:44.472 --> 00:39:46.092
inhibited different parts of the response.

699
00:39:46.272 --> 00:39:49.932
So when you inhibit type one interferon signaling, this is the dashed purple line,

700
00:39:50.612 --> 00:39:53.752
it goes back to baseline. So type one interferon signaling is driving this whole

701
00:39:53.792 --> 00:39:55.912
response in the immune competent mice.

702
00:39:56.872 --> 00:39:59.192
When you inhibit natural killer cells in blue, it does not matter.

703
00:39:59.652 --> 00:40:02.332
And when you inhibit CD8 T cells, there's a bit of an effect.

704
00:40:03.412 --> 00:40:07.392
And indeed, we do see more proliferation of CD8 T cells in the spleens

705
00:40:07.412 --> 00:40:11.201
of the combination group. And when we co-culture those T cells and

706
00:40:11.252 --> 00:40:13.912
tumor cells, we do see more specific lysis of the tumor cells.

707
00:40:14.332 --> 00:40:17.592
So in this case, the viral mimicry is causing type one interferon signaling that

708
00:40:17.632 --> 00:40:19.412
brings in T cells to kill the tumor.

709
00:40:20.932 --> 00:40:24.892
What we also observed was interestingly different responses to epigenetic therapy

710
00:40:25.132 --> 00:40:27.332
in cell lines based on P53 mutant status.

711
00:40:27.852 --> 00:40:30.232
So this was work done by my postdoc, James MacDonald.

712
00:40:30.892 --> 00:40:34.832
And here we're looking at TEs upregulated by HDAC inhibitors, DNMT

713
00:40:34.852 --> 00:40:38.552
inhibitors, or the combination of both, where the blue are the wild type cell lines

714
00:40:38.572 --> 00:40:39.852
and the red are the mutant cell lines.

715
00:40:40.332 --> 00:40:44.051
When you look at all TEs, there's a bit more upregulation in the wild type than the

716
00:40:44.092 --> 00:40:47.561
mutant. But over here, when you look at these immunogenic SINE repeats, it's much

717
00:40:47.592 --> 00:40:48.202
more dramatic.

718
00:40:49.032 --> 00:40:51.452
And so we wanted to understand what's going on here.

719
00:40:51.492 --> 00:40:55.392
So when we think about P53 mutations in cancer, there are plenty of null mutations,

720
00:40:55.472 --> 00:40:58.542
but actually the most common mutations are in the DNA binding domain.

721
00:40:59.072 --> 00:41:02.672
These alter P53's binding to its canonical targets.

722
00:41:02.712 --> 00:41:06.052
You still will have P53 protein, but it's not going to be able to bind and activate

723
00:41:06.092 --> 00:41:07.052
its canonical targets.

724
00:41:08.072 --> 00:41:11.492
And when you look in the literature, P53 represses

725
00:41:11.532 --> 00:41:13.792
transposable elements in flies and zebrafish.

726
00:41:14.612 --> 00:41:18.552
John Abrams' lab has shown that P53 can bind directly to

727
00:41:18.592 --> 00:41:22.191
line elements to suppress them. But Ting Wang

728
00:41:22.292 --> 00:41:26.072
and Guillaume Burk have shown that P53 can bind to endogenous retroviruses and

729
00:41:26.112 --> 00:41:26.792
upregulate them.

730
00:41:27.652 --> 00:41:31.192
And finally, Andrey Gudkov's lab showed that fibroblasts from Li-Fraumeni

731
00:41:31.312 --> 00:41:35.112
patients upregulate these TEs baseline and activate interferon signaling when

732
00:41:35.152 --> 00:41:38.932
treated with DNMT inhibitors. So there was a lot of information in the literature,

733
00:41:39.112 --> 00:41:40.872
both in terms of activation and repression.

734
00:41:41.912 --> 00:41:45.312
And so we wanted to learn what P53 was doing in our

735
00:41:45.352 --> 00:41:47.782
hands and started with wild type P53.

736
00:41:48.592 --> 00:41:51.272
We use a drug called Nutlin to activate wild type P53.

737
00:41:51.552 --> 00:41:55.212
This inhibits the interaction with MDM2, which normally leads to P53

738
00:41:55.232 --> 00:41:58.612
degradation. And so you can see over here, it's stabilizing wild type

739
00:41:58.652 --> 00:41:59.252
P53.

740
00:42:00.672 --> 00:42:04.392
We looked for where P53 was going on the chromatin upon Nutlin

741
00:42:04.432 --> 00:42:08.412
treatment, and you can see it binds to a lot of these SINE TEs, as well as LTRs and

742
00:42:08.452 --> 00:42:11.811
lines, and at the individual locus level, lots of LTRs, as well

743
00:42:11.852 --> 00:42:13.012
as SINES.

744
00:42:14.252 --> 00:42:18.212
And we treat with AZO. We also see this binding to different TEs across the

745
00:42:18.232 --> 00:42:21.792
genome. In terms of the transcriptional effects, Nutlin

746
00:42:21.892 --> 00:42:25.752
increases transcription of TEs, so does the DNMT inhibitor,

747
00:42:26.252 --> 00:42:28.652
and the combination of both is more than either one alone.

748
00:42:29.172 --> 00:42:32.592
This is a volcano plot with the cutoff for significance here, and this would be an

749
00:42:32.652 --> 00:42:36.084
increase or a decrease.So to put this together,

750
00:42:36.684 --> 00:42:40.324
at least for LTRs in the genome, it looks like DNMT inhibitors remove

751
00:42:40.364 --> 00:42:44.284
methylation, and wild-type p53 will go to these LTRs to

752
00:42:44.344 --> 00:42:45.364
activate transcription.

753
00:42:46.864 --> 00:42:50.304
As we were publishing this, Galina Slivonova's lab came out with really nice work

754
00:42:50.404 --> 00:42:53.864
showing localization of p53 to IRVs upon nutlin treatment,

755
00:42:54.264 --> 00:42:57.284
resulting in transcription of these and downstream interferon signaling.

756
00:42:58.824 --> 00:43:01.184
So we can consolidate these data for this

757
00:43:02.064 --> 00:43:05.964
model of how wild-type p53 works. However, most cancers do

758
00:43:06.004 --> 00:43:09.433
not have wild-type p53. And so we wanted to learn more about how TEs are

759
00:43:09.444 --> 00:43:12.334
regulated in the context of mutant and null p53.

760
00:43:13.464 --> 00:43:17.384
To do this, we made an isogenic cell line model where we took our wild-type cell

761
00:43:17.424 --> 00:43:21.164
line and edited it with CRISPR-Cas9 to make an R175H hotspot

762
00:43:21.204 --> 00:43:25.034
mutant. You can see that this has high levels baseline, and then the null cell line

763
00:43:25.044 --> 00:43:26.073
where there's no p53.

764
00:43:26.984 --> 00:43:29.004
And this is work done by my PhD student, Trace Walker.

765
00:43:29.884 --> 00:43:33.784
When we compare TE expression in the mutant versus wild type, we see

766
00:43:33.804 --> 00:43:35.464
both upregulation and downregulation.

767
00:43:36.573 --> 00:43:40.404
And we compare the null versus the wild type, there is a huge upregulation of TEs.

768
00:43:40.484 --> 00:43:41.264
This is interesting.

769
00:43:43.044 --> 00:43:46.744
To learn more about why these TEs are upregulated, we looked at expression of

770
00:43:46.784 --> 00:43:50.324
regulators of DNA methylation. And so you can see in this null cell line, the

771
00:43:50.344 --> 00:43:53.774
DNMT1 protein is much reduced compared to the others, and

772
00:43:53.844 --> 00:43:57.744
UHRF1, which is an important protein that helps DNMT1 methylate the DNA,

773
00:43:57.804 --> 00:43:58.724
is also much lower.

774
00:44:00.404 --> 00:44:03.964
When we assess genome-wide DNA methylation with a dot blot, we also see that it is

775
00:44:04.044 --> 00:44:07.964
lower in the null cell line. And double-stranded RNA, by the

776
00:44:08.044 --> 00:44:11.864
J2 antibody, is much higher. So overall, p53 loss leads to

777
00:44:11.964 --> 00:44:15.384
loss of DNA methylation across the genome and more immunogenic double-stranded RNA.

778
00:44:17.224 --> 00:44:21.024
When we look at differentially methylated regions in this null compared to

779
00:44:21.104 --> 00:44:24.664
wild type, we also see that a lot of these are going to be at the transposable

780
00:44:24.704 --> 00:44:26.944
elements, including SINEs, LINEs, and LTRs.

781
00:44:27.344 --> 00:44:30.864
There are plenty that do gain methylation, but more that lose it, and that there

782
00:44:30.884 --> 00:44:31.264
really are

783
00:44:32.444 --> 00:44:35.824
very few significant alterations in the mutant versus the wild type.

784
00:44:35.864 --> 00:44:37.944
So this is really a phenotype of the null p53.

785
00:44:40.084 --> 00:44:43.744
In addition, when we look at methylation versus expression, so here, these plots on

786
00:44:43.783 --> 00:44:47.564
the X-axis going to the right will be increase in methylation, to the

787
00:44:47.584 --> 00:44:50.744
left will be decrease. And then on the X-axis is the fold change.

788
00:44:51.104 --> 00:44:53.644
So increase in expression, decrease in expression.

789
00:44:53.684 --> 00:44:56.924
There's very few that are changed in this R175H versus wild type

790
00:44:57.324 --> 00:45:00.804
compared to the null versus wild type, where many of these are losing methylation

791
00:45:00.824 --> 00:45:04.604
and gaining expression, which would be loss of methylation leads to

792
00:45:04.644 --> 00:45:07.584
upregulation, compared to other elements where there might be

793
00:45:07.624 --> 00:45:09.624
methylation-independent re-expression.

794
00:45:09.644 --> 00:45:12.454
For example, loss of p53 transcriptional silencing.

795
00:45:15.084 --> 00:45:18.884
So knowing all of this, we then wanted to compare the response to DNMT

796
00:45:18.944 --> 00:45:19.494
inhibitors in the

797
00:45:20.724 --> 00:45:24.584
different p53 status. So for the wild type, we see that the DNMT

798
00:45:24.624 --> 00:45:26.304
inhibitor upregulates lots of TEs.

799
00:45:26.784 --> 00:45:29.704
These mostly lose methylation and gain expression as we would expect.

800
00:45:31.174 --> 00:45:34.784
The R175H mutant is much less responsive, which is very interesting,

801
00:45:35.144 --> 00:45:39.043
potentially due to the lack of this hotspot mutant binding at the

802
00:45:40.364 --> 00:45:44.084
LTRs where the wild-type p53

803
00:45:44.104 --> 00:45:44.444
binds.

804
00:45:45.804 --> 00:45:47.924
And then the null has a much bigger response.

805
00:45:47.964 --> 00:45:51.864
There's a much bigger upregulation upon DNMT inhibitor. You can see this over here.

806
00:45:52.584 --> 00:45:55.014
Lots of TEs are losing methylation and gaining expression.

807
00:45:56.964 --> 00:46:00.924
And indeed, these p53 null cells are the most responsive to DNMT inhibitor.

808
00:46:00.964 --> 00:46:04.824
So this is a bubble plot where red is a higher fold change, blue

809
00:46:04.904 --> 00:46:06.784
is lower, and then the size

810
00:46:07.784 --> 00:46:09.324
is correlated with significance.

811
00:46:09.924 --> 00:46:13.764
The first column is wild type, AZA treated, then R175H, then

812
00:46:13.804 --> 00:46:17.224
null. And you can see that the interferon-stimulated genes are highest in the null

813
00:46:17.444 --> 00:46:18.724
cell line when they're treated with AZA.

814
00:46:19.924 --> 00:46:23.864
And my student has a poster on Tuesday afternoon on this work.

815
00:46:24.444 --> 00:46:27.344
Please go and talk to him about it because it's really interesting, and I think we

816
00:46:27.404 --> 00:46:31.364
still have a lot of questions in terms of how the signaling is working.

817
00:46:32.504 --> 00:46:36.104
But I also wanted to bring up this idea of chronic TE expression interferon

818
00:46:36.224 --> 00:46:38.633
resistance. So this paper from Charles Ischek and colleagues.

819
00:46:39.544 --> 00:46:43.344
In terms of this, we do see the highest upregulation of TEs in

820
00:46:43.384 --> 00:46:47.164
interferon in the p53 null cells, but this could eventually be bad.

821
00:46:47.244 --> 00:46:50.844
Where we contributed a little bit to this paper with an immune

822
00:46:50.883 --> 00:46:54.784
competent model of ovarian cancer, where we compared p53 wild

823
00:46:54.883 --> 00:46:58.764
type to null treatment with AZA. And so in the wild type, the light

824
00:46:58.784 --> 00:47:02.514
blue here, treatment with AZA does seem to work better than the p53

825
00:47:02.744 --> 00:47:06.424
null in green treatment with AZA. And so I do think we have to think about the idea

826
00:47:06.464 --> 00:47:10.224
of chronic viral mimicry interferon and eventual resistance.

827
00:47:10.824 --> 00:47:13.424
And this will change how these are being translated to the clinic.

828
00:47:16.184 --> 00:47:20.064
So we can put this together. I tried to pull different published papers in terms

829
00:47:20.104 --> 00:47:24.064
of how p53 regulates human TEs specifically, where on the left side we have

830
00:47:24.124 --> 00:47:27.984
LTRs where wild-type p53 generally upregulates these.

831
00:47:28.024 --> 00:47:31.624
DNA methylation silences them. While there's more evidence for wild-type p53

832
00:47:31.644 --> 00:47:34.344
repressing LINEs, and DNA methylation silences these, too.

833
00:47:35.984 --> 00:47:39.484
Beyond this, we do see that p53 loss reduces DNA methylation

834
00:47:39.504 --> 00:47:42.384
genome-wide, amplifying the effects of DNMT inhibitors.

835
00:47:43.024 --> 00:47:46.874
In addition, this hotspot mutant R175H alters TE transcription,

836
00:47:47.304 --> 00:47:48.744
but not via DNA methylation.

837
00:47:49.764 --> 00:47:53.244
So we need to figure out more about how this p53 is

838
00:47:53.284 --> 00:47:56.224
affecting DNMTs genome-wide, and thus DNA methylation.

839
00:47:58.184 --> 00:48:01.644
Okay. So finally, I wanted to present a few slides on

840
00:48:02.304 --> 00:48:05.804
analysis of patient data. So of course, with all of this in cell lines and mouse

841
00:48:05.864 --> 00:48:06.204
models,

842
00:48:07.104 --> 00:48:10.904
in general, we're going from TE induction to interferon to infiltration of

843
00:48:10.944 --> 00:48:14.564
immune cells. We wanted to analyze data from patients to see if this was occurring

844
00:48:14.644 --> 00:48:18.224
baseline in the patients as well. And we were very fortunate to work with Dale

845
00:48:18.244 --> 00:48:22.064
Garsed and David Bowtell, who have a consortium that is led by Dr.

846
00:48:22.184 --> 00:48:25.384
Pearce looking at high-grade serous ovarian cancer patients.

847
00:48:25.514 --> 00:48:25.964
And so,

848
00:48:26.904 --> 00:48:30.424
this is a disease where the standard of care is surgery followed by

849
00:48:30.444 --> 00:48:33.984
chemotherapy. And unfortunately, most patients do become resistant and their

850
00:48:34.004 --> 00:48:37.772
disease recurs.And so this consortium has a group

851
00:48:37.832 --> 00:48:41.352
of long-term survivors, which would be over 10 years for this disease, moderate

852
00:48:41.392 --> 00:48:44.772
term, which is two to 10 years, and short-term, which is less than two years.

853
00:48:45.832 --> 00:48:48.812
And they've already published that these long-term survivors are characterized by

854
00:48:48.832 --> 00:48:52.792
deficiencies in homologous recombination as well as more infiltration of B

855
00:48:52.852 --> 00:48:54.372
and T cells, which makes a lot of sense.

856
00:48:55.732 --> 00:48:58.652
And we, of course, were curious about transposable element expression in these

857
00:48:58.692 --> 00:49:02.052
long-term survivors. And so this is unpublished work led by my student, Kevin

858
00:49:02.112 --> 00:49:05.792
Nestler. He compared TE expression in the long-term

859
00:49:05.852 --> 00:49:09.632
survivors versus the short-term survivors, and we do see increased TE expression in

860
00:49:09.652 --> 00:49:11.392
general here. This is a volcano plot.

861
00:49:12.252 --> 00:49:15.852
Just to pull some out, LTR-12C, which is often upregulated by DNMT

862
00:49:15.872 --> 00:49:19.712
inhibitors, is much higher in the long-term survivors in maroon, as is

863
00:49:19.792 --> 00:49:20.852
LTR-25.

864
00:49:22.612 --> 00:49:26.352
When we look at the locus-specific level, we do see upregulation of line one and

865
00:49:26.672 --> 00:49:30.492
LTR elements. You can see line one full length here is really increased in the

866
00:49:30.532 --> 00:49:34.312
long-term survivors. And I wanted to point out HERV-W, which is

867
00:49:34.332 --> 00:49:38.232
all the way up here. This is actually an ERV that encodes an

868
00:49:38.272 --> 00:49:41.852
immunosuppressive protein that can be expressed on the surface of cells, and it's

869
00:49:41.872 --> 00:49:44.322
downregulated in the long-term survivors, which is quite interesting.

870
00:49:46.012 --> 00:49:49.832
So after seeing these results, Kevin decided to do unsupervised

871
00:49:49.852 --> 00:49:53.392
clustering of the patient samples based on TE expression.

872
00:49:53.542 --> 00:49:57.111
And so here on the left, we're looking at lines, LTRs, and SINEs.

873
00:49:57.212 --> 00:49:58.752
So there's a high-expressing group here,

874
00:49:59.932 --> 00:50:03.112
there's a low-expressing group, C2 in the middle, and there's a medium-expressing

875
00:50:03.152 --> 00:50:05.612
group on the right, and each column here is a patient.

876
00:50:07.032 --> 00:50:10.712
So when we look at the survival of these groups, the cluster C1 in

877
00:50:10.752 --> 00:50:14.612
teal that has the highest TE expression has significantly longer

878
00:50:14.672 --> 00:50:17.012
overall survival as well as progression-free survival.

879
00:50:18.632 --> 00:50:21.592
We wanted to know if there were molecular features that explained this upregulation

880
00:50:21.612 --> 00:50:23.432
of TEs and potentially longer survival.

881
00:50:23.832 --> 00:50:26.252
This is a busy slide, but the short answer is no.

882
00:50:27.012 --> 00:50:30.452
So you can see the high TE, low, and moderate TE groups here.

883
00:50:30.972 --> 00:50:34.752
There were no significant differences on age, smoking status, HRD status,

884
00:50:35.152 --> 00:50:38.532
P53, or BRCA. And I want to make a note about P53.

885
00:50:38.772 --> 00:50:42.682
Basically, all of these patients have P53 mutations, so we have no wild type to

886
00:50:42.712 --> 00:50:43.831
compare to, unfortunately,

887
00:50:44.812 --> 00:50:45.592
because of the disease.

888
00:50:46.632 --> 00:50:50.202
So there was no specific genetic alteration that associated with this.

889
00:50:51.332 --> 00:50:55.312
If we look at epigenetic regulators, there also were not clear ones that stood out

890
00:50:55.392 --> 00:50:59.132
except for KAT2A. This is a histone acetyltransferase that was higher

891
00:50:59.152 --> 00:51:01.632
expressed in the C1 group, and so we're looking into this further.

892
00:51:03.512 --> 00:51:07.372
Finally, we do see a small change in methylation at these inverted-repeat Alus.

893
00:51:07.432 --> 00:51:10.472
So again, these inverted-repeat Alu elements can make these hairpins that are

894
00:51:10.492 --> 00:51:13.752
sensed by MDA5, activating type I interferon response.

895
00:51:13.832 --> 00:51:17.412
This is DNA methylation analysis of methylation array data, where

896
00:51:17.512 --> 00:51:21.432
zero is no methylation, one is 100% methylation, and the

897
00:51:21.442 --> 00:51:25.332
density on the y-axis is how many elements are you adding up that have zero or

898
00:51:25.432 --> 00:51:29.121
100. So you can see a lot of these IR Alus are 90% methylated.

899
00:51:29.532 --> 00:51:33.512
And if you compare C2 and C3 to C1 in the teal here, there is a little

900
00:51:33.552 --> 00:51:34.492
bit less methylation there.

901
00:51:36.952 --> 00:51:40.672
So finally, we want to know if these patients had increased immune cell

902
00:51:40.712 --> 00:51:44.412
infiltration. And first, we used CytoSort to

903
00:51:44.472 --> 00:51:47.841
estimate the percentage of immune cells in these samples.

904
00:51:48.312 --> 00:51:51.412
And in general, there are more B cells in the C1 cluster.

905
00:51:51.532 --> 00:51:54.952
There's more follicular helper T cells, fewer neutrophils, and fewer

906
00:51:55.012 --> 00:51:55.732
macrophages.

907
00:51:56.772 --> 00:52:00.742
We were fortunate to have access to multiplex IHC on a subset of these samples, and

908
00:52:00.772 --> 00:52:04.032
this really confirms a lot of the data from the

909
00:52:04.412 --> 00:52:08.272
CytoSort, where there's more PD-1 positive immune cells and

910
00:52:08.312 --> 00:52:11.912
CD8 positive T cells and B cells. So this is really going along with more

911
00:52:11.932 --> 00:52:13.072
infiltrating lymphocytes.

912
00:52:15.072 --> 00:52:18.412
In terms of what can be upregulating this innate immune response,

913
00:52:19.332 --> 00:52:23.232
besides the IR Alus, full-length line ones that are reverse

914
00:52:23.292 --> 00:52:27.192
transcribing can activate cGAS-STING signaling with DNA-RNA

915
00:52:27.232 --> 00:52:30.352
hybrids. This was published by Marty Taylor and colleagues to activate type I

916
00:52:30.372 --> 00:52:34.052
interferon. And when Kevin looks at the expression of these full-length lines, they

917
00:52:34.112 --> 00:52:35.532
are increased in the C1 group.

918
00:52:37.072 --> 00:52:40.652
When we look at the IR Alu elements that can also activate this response, these

919
00:52:40.692 --> 00:52:43.092
were also increased, so we could not narrow it down to one or the other.

920
00:52:45.242 --> 00:52:48.832
And then finally, because type I interferon is induced by this signaling, we wanted

921
00:52:48.872 --> 00:52:50.492
to measure type I interferon expression.

922
00:52:50.822 --> 00:52:53.401
And interferon alpha, in this case, is significantly increased.

923
00:52:55.452 --> 00:52:59.182
So in summary, the samples with high TE expression have longer survival, higher

924
00:52:59.272 --> 00:53:01.812
levels of PD-1 positive immune cells, T and B cells,

925
00:53:02.612 --> 00:53:04.772
and express potentially immunogenic TEs.

926
00:53:05.472 --> 00:53:08.212
And current work is determining how this is really being regulated in these

927
00:53:08.232 --> 00:53:08.972
patients baseline.

928
00:53:10.712 --> 00:53:14.692
So overall, we've talked about epigenetic therapies that open the chromatin to

929
00:53:14.752 --> 00:53:17.482
activate type I interferon through transposable element RNA.

930
00:53:19.152 --> 00:53:21.652
Wild type P53 transcriptionally regulates TEs.

931
00:53:22.032 --> 00:53:25.502
Mutations in this gene alter the viral mimicry response in cancer, which may have

932
00:53:25.532 --> 00:53:26.942
important therapeutic implications.

933
00:53:27.632 --> 00:53:30.752
And then when we have high TE expression in these ovarian cancer patients, this

934
00:53:30.772 --> 00:53:34.632
correlates with increased T and B cell infiltration, type I interferon, and longer

935
00:53:34.712 --> 00:53:35.112
survival.

936
00:53:37.112 --> 00:53:37.872
And so finally,

937
00:53:38.832 --> 00:53:42.272
I was fortunate to work with Cathy Burns to write a review on transposable elements

938
00:53:42.292 --> 00:53:45.792
in cancer for "Cancer Discovery," where we describe how

939
00:53:45.852 --> 00:53:49.272
transposable elements contribute to six of the defined hallmarks of cancer.

940
00:53:49.682 --> 00:53:52.512
And the "Cancer Discovery" team asked me to include this here because apparently

941
00:53:52.532 --> 00:53:54.832
it's being published now, so you can see it.

942
00:53:55.752 --> 00:53:58.272
And we proposed this as a new hallmark of cancer, actually.

943
00:53:59.082 --> 00:54:02.482
So this is for you all to peruse if you're interested in learning more about

944
00:54:02.572 --> 00:54:03.912
transposable elements in cancer.

945
00:54:06.052 --> 00:54:06.272
Okay.

946
00:54:07.552 --> 00:54:10.652
And so I want to thank everyone on my team who did the work, as well as our funding

947
00:54:10.672 --> 00:54:12.812
and many collaborators who I've already mentioned.

948
00:54:13.072 --> 00:54:16.832
And thank you for your attention. I'm happy to take any questions.

949
00:54:22.892 --> 00:54:25.052
Hi. Wonderful talk. I have two questions.

950
00:54:25.132 --> 00:54:26.142
My first question is,

951
00:54:27.152 --> 00:54:30.672
P53 has so many targets and so many binding elements,

952
00:54:31.312 --> 00:54:35.102
so your discovery of specific regulation of lines and SINEs,

953
00:54:35.892 --> 00:54:39.612
could it be an indirect effect, and does it also impinge on

954
00:54:39.692 --> 00:54:40.352
other loci?

955
00:54:41.224 --> 00:54:43.944
Absolutely. So I think that there are both direct and indirect effects.

956
00:54:44.364 --> 00:54:48.193
We physically tried to separate out which ones we see wild-type P53 actually

957
00:54:48.204 --> 00:54:50.444
binding to in terms of the ones that are being transcribed.

958
00:54:50.924 --> 00:54:54.904
But we also see alteration in transcription of elements where P53 is

959
00:54:54.944 --> 00:54:58.394
not binding directly. So for example, on the P53 null,

960
00:54:59.224 --> 00:55:02.964
the TEs that are upregulated are not a lot of the ones where it's binding directly.

961
00:55:03.044 --> 00:55:05.524
So I think that's more of a result of DNA methylation loss.

962
00:55:05.624 --> 00:55:07.344
And so that's why we have these data.

963
00:55:07.384 --> 00:55:11.364
We're now actually combining H3K9 methylation, H3K4

964
00:55:11.384 --> 00:55:14.884
methylation cut and run to see how the chromatin is being altered.

965
00:55:14.904 --> 00:55:17.984
But yes, that is why P53 is really hard to work with.

966
00:55:18.014 --> 00:55:18.014
Yeah.

967
00:55:18.024 --> 00:55:21.704
And we also tried to use NETland rather than DNA damaging to avoid the DNA damage

968
00:55:21.744 --> 00:55:22.764
response. Yeah.

969
00:55:22.804 --> 00:55:24.524
My second question is more specific.

970
00:55:24.604 --> 00:55:27.804
So the data you showed that all of your

971
00:55:28.384 --> 00:55:32.304
high-grade serous ovarian cancer patients had P53 mutation, that is expected.

972
00:55:32.664 --> 00:55:35.044
But did you try to classify the mutations, maybe

973
00:55:35.884 --> 00:55:39.424
hotspot versus non-hotspot? Does it segregate your

974
00:55:39.684 --> 00:55:41.524
long-term and short survivors?

975
00:55:41.704 --> 00:55:44.224
